  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/splice
  [2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Event/target

You have the right thinking, but you should start with an array that will always give you want you want instead of hoping it will give you want you want.

One suggestion is to read up on the `this` context in event handlers as that can simplify your code a lot like below.

For each click we will use `this` (the clicked div) to get the current color, then you can [filter][1] out that current color, so you&#39;re left with an array with all the colors, but that one.

Now your makeColor() will just work since it has an array that is meant for it to begin with.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    ad = document.querySelectorAll(&quot;.all div&quot;)
    colors = [&#39;yellow&#39;, &#39;red&#39;, &#39;blue&#39;, &#39;cornsilk&#39;]

    ad.forEach(f =&gt; {
      f.addEventListener(&#39;click&#39;, function() {
        let cc = this.style.backgroundColor;
        let diffColors = colors.filter(color =&gt; color !== cc);

        function makeColor() {
          return diffColors[Math.floor(Math.random() * colors.length)]
        };

        this.style.backgroundColor = makeColor();
      });
    });

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;all&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div&gt;hello&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


  [1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Array/filter

